nted history of the institutional gatekeepers, confident of the validity of socially biased measures of merit, seeking to select tomorrow's leadership class from among their economically privileged clientele. Acceptance in prestigious colleges still remains beyond the reach of most students except those from high-income professional families. Ultimately, the author suggests reforms that would move America's top schools toward becoming genuine academic meritocracies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aEducation, HigherzUnited States. 0aElite (Social sciences)zUnited States. 0aUniversities and collegeszUnited StatesxAdmission. 4aEducation. 4aSociology -- Education and Society. 7aEDUCATION / Higher.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080476828340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804768283423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780804768283/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles